snippet.textDisplay: Angst and pressure aside; all comedy is 'your' own concerns, fears, insecurities and unsolvable problems: on stage, ironically stating your troubles, darkest-secrets, cringiest embarrassments, make people laugh. Being deceptive with yourself or holding onto your self-esteem will never open the door to good material; the mortification that causes you to hold back the honest truth in your routine is indicative of the humor in the story: basically, If you're humiliated by the joke/story then it's good, a comedic-gold-mine.

snippet.textDisplay:
SNL? The tv show that no one cares about?

As to jokes, three things. First, there is a difference between funny and cruel. Making fun of handicapped people, mentally ill people, etc crosses that line. Research the career of Andrew Dice Clay and learn from his mistakes.

Second, do what Milton Beryl once advised. He said to tell yourself the joke in your head first. If it makes you cringe do not say it.

Third, a good comedian is an expert on rhetoric who has fun and makes people laugh. Cussing, sexual stuff, and poltical sucking up is not comedy.
snippet.textOriginal:
SNL? The tv show that no one cares about? 

As to jokes, three things. First, there is a difference between funny and cruel. Making fun of handicapped people, mentally ill people, etc crosses that line. Research the career of Andrew Dice Clay and learn from his mistakes.

Second, do what Milton Beryl once advised. He said to tell yourself the joke in your head first. If it makes you cringe do not say it. 

Third, a good comedian is an expert on rhetoric who has fun and makes people laugh. Cussing, sexual stuff, and poltical sucking up is not comedy.
